# AWS IAM MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication)

## What I did:

- Navigated to IAM service in AWS console
- Selected IAM user and opened security credentials
- Enabled Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
- Configured virtual MFA using authenticator app
- Scanned QR code and verified OTP codes
- Successfully activated MFA for IAM user
- Tested login with password + OTP
- Tested differnt MFA option such as security passkey, authenticator app .



## Key Learnings:

- MFA adds an extra layer of security beyond passwords
- Authentication requires something you know (password) + something you have (OTP)
- Even if credentials are compromised, MFA prevents unauthorized access
- AWS supports virtual, hardware, and SMS-based MFA
- Virtual MFA (Authenticator apps) is most commonly used



## Hands-on Summary:

- Enabled MFA using Google/Microsoft Authenticator
- Verified setup using two consecutive OTP codes
- Logged out and tested login flow:
  - Password required ✅
  - OTP required ✅
- Confirmed MFA is working correctly



## Mistakes to Avoid:

- Not enabling MFA on root account
- Relying only on passwords for security
- Losing access to MFA device without backup
- Sharing OTP codes with others



## Security Insight:

- MFA protects against:
  - Password leaks
  - Phishing attacks
  - Credential stuffing
- Even if attacker gets password, access is blocked without OTP
- Critical for securing high-privilege accounts



## Real-World Understanding:

- MFA is mandatory in production environments
- Used in combination with IAM roles and least privilege
- Essential control in compliance frameworks (SOC2, ISO 27001)


